paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.spark.sql.Encoders
import org.apache.spark.sql.functions._

case class ScoreOnDisk(srcUniqueId: String, dstUniqueId: String, score: Double, source: String)
val scoreSchema = Encoders.product[ScoreOnDisk].schema

def readScoresPRD(scoreName: String) = {
    spark
        .read
        .option("header", "true")
        .schema(scoreSchema)
        .csv(s"$scoresPRDFolder/$scoreName")
        .withColumnRenamed("srcUniqueId", "tag")
}

def readScoresPRD2(scoreName: String) = {
    spark
        .read
        .option("header", "true")
        .schema(scoreSchema)
        .csv(s"$scoresPRD2Folder/$scoreName")
        .withColumnRenamed("srcUniqueId", "tag")
}

import org.apache.spark.sql.functions.{coalesce, lit}

val full_overlap = fscore
    .join(blscore, 
            fscore("dstUniqueId") === blscore("dstUniqueId") &&
            fscore("tag") === blscore("tag"),
            "fullouter")
     .select(coalesce($"fscore.dstUniqueId", $"blscore.dstUniqueId") as "dstUniqueId",  
             coalesce($"fscore.tag", $"blscore.tag") as "tag", 
             $"fscore.score" as "f_score", 
             $"blscore.score" as "bl_score")
             
val overlap = full_overlap.filter(col("f_score").isNotNull && col("bl_score").isNotNull).as("overlap")
val f_not_bl = full_overlap.filter(col("f_score").isNotNull && col("bl_score").isNull).as("f_not_bl")
val bl_not_f = full_overlap.filter(col("f_score").isNull && col("bl_score").isNotNull).as("bl_not_f")

paragraphs.text:
%md
#### Distribution of users per tags

The goal of this metric is to check that the majority of the users are not heavy reader users and that fact is reflected in the recommendations. For that, is required to calculate the number of tags that each user has and then group again the users per number of tags. The expected result is that almost all the users have less than *N* tags (to review the value, an 20 tags looks a good indication in the moment of the creation of this document) 

The graphs shows:
- users per tag in ALS output
- users per tag in Business Rules output
- users per tag in final combination output

paragraphs.text:
// Tags per user for ALS output

// first count tags per user
val fscore_user_tags = fscore
    .filter($"score" > valid_threshold)
    .groupBy("dstUniqueId")
        .agg(count(lit(1.0)).alias("number_of_tags"))
    .orderBy($"number_of_tags".desc)
    
// group per count for distribution
val distribution_fscore_user_tags = fscore_user_tags
    .groupBy("number_of_tags")
        .agg(count(lit(1.0)).alias("count_number_of_tags"))
    .orderBy($"number_of_tags")
    
z.show(distribution_fscore_user_tags)
